post_text:
Please find attached to this post the Student Attestation Form. All Students must provide an Attestation Form to enter our buildings.

Yellow Attestation Forms have started being sent home. You are welcome to print these forms (on white paper) at home so they can be filled out before sending your student to school or having your student ride one of the school buses.

Students who do not present this Attestation Form when entering the building will be unable to attend class until they have been screened by building staff. If the district screening process results in isolation, parents will be asked to pick the student(s) up from school.

If we learn you may have been exposed to COVID-19 during your visit, we will only share this information with public health officials. We will not use this information for any other purpose.

We know the impact Covid has had on our economy and that it may have created hardship for some of our families. You may find that you now qualify for Free and Reduced Lunch. When you qualify for Free and Reduced Lunch you also qualify for an additional food benefit through the DSHS Pandemic-EBT program.

If you have not signed up for Free and Reduced Lunch for the 2019-20 school year and believe you now qualify, please access the districts online application by Sunday, June 28th. You can find the online application on the Nine Mile Falls School District website.
https://www.schoolnutritionandfitness.com/index.php?sid=1521645850619&page=lunchapps

You can also learn how to access the Pandemic-EBT program by clicking this link.
https://medium.com/@waOSPI/what-is-pandemic-ebt-a7a086fcaf94

The deadline to submit your Free and Reduced paperwork through the online portal is Sunday, June 28th.

post_text: Congratulations Graduating!!! We are so very proud of the Class of 2020.
shared_text:
BobandKim Buckley‚ÄéNine Mile Falls School District
June 13 at 1:23 PM ¬∑

When Madelyn started kindergarten in 2007, I remember being told that this was the Class of 2020. I couldn't picture that little girl as a high school graduate at that point and certainly could never have imagined what this year would look like for her. We have so much gratitude for the Nine Mile School District and all the amazing teachers, administrators and support staff, past and present. You have always worked hard with and for our kids. We are especially grateful for the extra effort you've put in these past few months helping our students succeed.

post_text:
People are inherently good!

Today is a sad day as the beautifully carved Eagle was removed from its perch. As many of you know, our Eagle resided between Nine Mile Falls Elementary School and the District Office.

Through anonymous tips, the perpetrators of this vandalism have been identified and the crime has been reported to the Spokane County Sheriff‚Äôs Department. We are grateful to report that this act was not done by anyone living in our community.

Those of us who loved our Eagle continue to remind ourselves that we are surrounded by amazing people!

Nine Mile Falls is the best possible community where people are inherently good. #9MileProud

Happy MAY DAY Nine Mile!
What is May Day? A celebration of the return of spring.
How do you celebrate May Day? Tradition would have it that people would leave a paper basket or cone filled with spring flowers (think dandelions or other wildflowers), and sweets on each other's doorstops - usually anonymously.

Eleven Nine Mile Falls School District Destination Imagination Teams competed over the weekend in Richland at the Eastern Washington Regional Competition.

Out of the 96 teams competing, in seven categories, and three age levels, Nine Mile Falls teams brought home TEN Medals and ONE Special Award!

Congratulations to all of the Destination Imagination teams! Wishing you luck as your prepare for State Competition which is being held March 27th and 28th.

**Special Thank You to all of the parents, extended families, coaches and support people that have made this program possible. The school district appreciates your gift of time, food/snacks, and your living rooms, as teams have prepared for this event.

At this time the district is not able to receive calls from outside lines and has limited lines that are able to call out. The school district is working with the phone vendor and is awaiting a timeline for the solution.

If you need to contact your school please email your students school building. Email links have been created for each secretary and posted on each buildings web page.

I am happy to announce a new 3rd Grade One Year Only teaching position at Lake Spokane Elementary. (If you have applied for other teaching positions this year or are a substitute in the Nine Mile Falls SD you need only submit a letter of interest)

At 3pm this afternoon the Lakeside High School Math Long Term Substitute position is set to close! Don't delay in getting your paperwork in if you are interested!!

If you haven't looked at the Athletic/Coaching Job Board you will want to know that -
8th Grade Football is looking for a Varsity Head Coach!
LHS Baseball is searching for a 2nd Assistant
LHS Girls Soccer is still looking to fill the 1st Assistant position
Coaching is as much a gift to our students as a gift to ourselves. If you haven't tried coaching in the Nine Mile Falls School District I highly recommend getting involved!!! #GoEagles

You know your staff loves you when they send you a goat! The Wishing Star Foundation visited the Nine Mile Falls School District Buildings today. Selena Goatmez charmed her way into the hearts of many staff and loosened the purse strings to secure donations from the district staff for the Wishing Star Foundation.

The love may have started at Lake Spokane Elementary but it was soon shared with the District Office. The District Office didn't want the High School to miss out which is why Mr. Pietz was next in line. I am not sure who sent the goat to Nine Mile Falls Elementary (LHS) but rumor has it that Mrs. Norstadt may have had a furry visitor....

On Saturday March 2nd, seven teams from the Nine Mile Falls School District (Elementary through High School) traveled to Richland, Washington, to compete at the Destination Imagination Eastern Washington Regional Competition ‚ÄîThe LARGEST Destination Imagination competition in our state this season.

Out of 95 teams, the Nine Mile Falls School District teams brought home 5 Medals and 3 Special Awards!

All of the teams worked very hard for months perfecting performances, building sets/props and engineering contraptions. Please be sure to recognize these students for their hard work and dedication preparing for this competition. #TeamNineMile
State Bound March 29th-30th

Heads-Up! The annual Lakeside Middle School ASB Eagle Fund Run Fundraiser starts TODAY!

Between Sept 14 and Oct 8, LMS students will be out in the area asking for money to support their Associated Student Body (ASB) activities. ASB activities include cultural, athletic, recreational, and social programs. This is the ONLY school-wide fundraiser and benefits ALL LMS students.

Checks can be made payable to Lakeside Middle School with the ASB account number 1187-330 on the memo line.

Thank you for supporting these great kids!

post_text:
Lakeside High School Football Players had the opportunity to volunteer in the community today. You may have seen some at Rosauers or heard about the team helping the food bank.

What you might never see is the group of young men that came to Nine Mile Falls Elementary and cleaned the weeds from the garden behind the school. Many of these students attended this school and reminisced about teachers and asking if those teachers were still teaching.

This same group took time to clean up the natural area and make it look a little more natural and a little less wild! This same group also took on the task of cleaning the outside of the district office, cleaning windows, scrubbing vinyl siding, and pulling weeds.

Thanks to the 2018-19 Football team the Nine MIle Falls Elementary and District Office are one step closer to being ready for school to start.
THANK YOU LAKESIDE FOOTBALL 2018-19

The Nine Mile Falls School District Maintenance team has been hard at work this summer. The Lakeside High School Football Field, Varsity and JV Baseball fields have all gone through a process called "DeCompaction" and have been top dressed and overseeded. The High School is also receiving a fresh coat of paint after being power-washed and caulked.

Lake Spokane Elementary courtyard has been refurbished to make it easier to maintain.

A big thank you to all of the maintenance, custodial and housekeeping staff for all the HARD work you provide the district through the summer months!!! Thank you for taking such good care of our facilities!!!

shared_text:
Lakeside High School
April 18, 2018 at 6:45 AM ¬∑

On April 19th at 12:15pm the Stevens Co. fire department will be staging a mock car crash in order to address the consequences of drunk driving and distracted driving before prom on the 21st. The event will be for Juniors and Seniors. We will start in the gym with a keynote speaker by the name of Darren Mattozzi, who will talk about losing his brother in a DUI accident. Students will then move to the track where a 2-car crash will be staged with student actors. Students will be extricated from cars, taken away in an ambulance, some will be pronounced dead and covered with a blanket, the drunk driver will be arrested and taken away in a police car, and as long as they are available Life flight will land and a student will be loaded. The event should end at 1:35pm.Counselors will be available afterwards for students that may experience distress due to watching the event. We hope that this is a great reminder of some of the life altering consequences that come with driving impaired.

post_text:
Another great weekend in the books!

On Saturday, four of our district‚Äôs Destination Imagination teams competed at the Washington State Destination Imagination Competition in Wenatchee.

Out of 99 teams competing, our students brought home 2 medals!

The 6th grade team, The Super Snazzy Disappearing Rainbows placed third in the Service Learning, Project Outreach Challenge.

The 7th grade team, The Girls Who Didn‚Äôt Wear Shoes took third place in the Scientific, Unlikely Attraction Challenge. They also had the highest Instant Challenge score in their challenge category.

All of the teams worked very hard for months perfecting their performances and building their sets, props and engineered contraptions. Please be sure to congratulate them on their accomplishment!

Thank you for your continued support of these students and this program.

It will be exciting to see what next year will bring for these amazing students!
